      ],
      "caption" : "A typical bear off position",
      "note" : "",
      "text" : "Pipcount Player: 51 pips - Opponent: 60 pips"
    },
    {
      "difficulty" : 2,
      "id" : "22aICAbG3j0AAA:MAEAAAAAAAAA",
      "tags" : [
        "holding",
        "cluster",
        "pipcount",
        "contact",
        "training"
      ],
      "caption" : "Typical Holding game",
      "note" : "Test",
      "text" : "My checkers: I know there are 42 pips on the closed board. Two checkers are missing on the 5th, so 32 pips. 1 checker on the 10th. That makes 42. 2 checkers on the 21st = 42. That makes 84. 1 checker on the 16th, that makes 100, + 1 checker on the 13th = total 113\n\nThere are certainly several ways to count the opponent’s checkers. For example, I mentally move the checker from 8 and 6 to 7, giving 11 × 7 = 77. \n2 checker on 5 = 87. \n2 checker on 2 = 91.\n\nWith a little practice, counting a position like this takes less than 5 seconds.\n"
    },
    {
      "difficulty" : 1,
      "id" : "AAAAsG0DAAAAAA:cAnkAAAAEAAE",
      "tags" : [
        "pipcount",
        "cluster"
      ],
      "caption" : "Reference Position 1:  5-Prime",
      "note" : "",
      "text" : "Multiply the midpoint of any 5-prime by 10 and you have just counted a cluster of ten checkers.\nThis position shows a 5-prime from the 4-point to the 8-point.\nThe 6-point is the midpoint and the count for these ten checkers = 60 pips (6 × 10.) This is so because 5's and 7's average out to 6's, and 4's and 8's also average out to 6's.\n\nPipCount = 60."
    },
    {
      "difficulty" : 1,
      "id" : "AAAAtm0DAAAAAA:cIkoARAAAAAE",
      "tags" : [
        "pipcount",
        "cluster"
      ],
      "caption" : "Reference Position 2:  Closed Board",
      "note" : "",
      "text" : "This is just a 5-prime around the 4-point plus two checkers on the ace point.\n\nPipCount = 42."
    },
    {
      "difficulty" : 1,
      "id" : "AAAAwOcDAAAAAA:cIkoARAAAAAE",
