    {
      "difficulty" : 1,
      "id" : "eB4AALA3AAAAAA:cAkuAWAAOAAE",
      "tags" : [
        "cluster",
        "pipcount"
      ],
      "caption" : "Using 5-Point as Key Point",
      "note" : "",
      "text" : "This position shows two examples of counting a cluster of eight checkers all at once as if they were eight 5's = 40.\n\nPlayer = 40. Opponent = 40."
    },
    {
      "difficulty" : 1,
      "id" : "AAAYCgAAMwEAAA:cAkuAWAAOAAE",
      "tags" : [
        "cluster",
        "pipcount"
      ],
      "caption" : "Using 20-Point as Key Point",
      "note" : "",
      "text" : "The 20-point (opponent's 5-point) is the most useful key point. All checkers in your opponent's home board should be counted as 20 plus the pips required to get to the 20-point.\n\nPlayer's count is 108 which can be visualized as five 20's + 4 (two each from the 22-point to the 20-point) + 4 (one from 24-point to 20 point).\n\nOpponent's count is 89, visualized as four 20's + 4 + 5 (for the checker on the bar)."
    },
    {
      "difficulty" : 1,
      "id" : "ANgAAAYADAAAAA:cAlqAAAAAAAE",
      "tags" : [
        "pipcount",
        "cluster"
      ],
      "caption" : "Mirror - Example 1",
      "note" : "",
      "text" : "Player: (20 + 5 = 25) × 2 = 50.\n\nOpponent: (13 + 12 = 25) × 2 = 50.\n\nPlayer = 50. Opponent = 50."
    },
    {
      "difficulty" : 1,
      "id" : "wAAYoAAAoAAAAA:cAlqAAAAAAAE",
      "tags" : [
        "pipcount",
        "cluster"
      ],
      "caption" : "Mirror - Example 2",
      "note" : "",
      "text" : "Player: (23 + 2 = 25) + (24 + 1 = 25) = 50 .\n\nOpponent: (18 + 7 = 25) × 2 = 50.\n\nPlayer = 50. Opponent = 50."
    },
    {
      "difficulty" : 1,
      "id" : "ttkYAQy43RSAIQ:cAkgATAACAAE",
      "tags" : [
        "pipcount",
        "cluster",
        "training"
      ],
      "caption" : "One-Way Mental Shift",
      "note" : "",
      "text" : "Player's checker can be easily counted in three clusters: 40 (eight 5's) + 33 (RP4 + 3 pips) + 64 (three 20's + 4) = 137.\n\nDivide Opponent's checkers into three clusters: 44 (5-prime + 4 pips forward, 2 each from the 7-point to the 5-point) + 33 (three 10's + 3 pips from 13 to 10) + 44 (two 20's + 4) = 121.\n\nPlayer = 137. Opponent = 121."
    },
    {
      "difficulty" : 1,
      "id" : "NrtFABTYtuMAIA:MIHlADAAEAAE",
      "tags" : [
        "pipcount",
        "training"
      ],
      "caption" : "",
      "note" : "",
      "text" : ""
    },
    {
      "difficulty" : 1,
      "id" : "2NbBAQawc8MHAA:cInlADAAEAAE",
      "tags" : [
        "pipcount",
        "cluster",
        "training"
      ],
      "caption" : "Two-Way Mental Shift",
      "note" : "",
      "text" : "Players's spare checkers on the 6- and 8- points are on the same side of the board. By shifting them one pip in opposite directions to the 7-point, a 5-prime is formed. Player's position can easily be counted in two clusters: 70 (5-prime) + 65 (five 13's) = 135.\n\nOpponent's spare checkers on the 8- and 13-points are on opposite sides of the board. By shifting them in the same direction, in this case left-to-right, a 5-prime is formed (RP1) and RP7 is also formed. Opponent's position can then be counted in three clusters: 60 + 40 + 42 (two 20's + 2) = 142.\n\nPlayer = 135. Opponent = 142."
    },
